Using fractional derivatives in these models introduces a memory effect, meaning past interactions within the host population influence current and future disease dynamics. This memory-driven acceleration can increase \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(R_0)$$\end{document} values as the disease ’remembers’ its past encounters and spreads more effectively. Understanding these relationships is crucial for predicting disease dynamics and implementing effective control measures.

